The paper discusses user preferences for automated assistance in software domains, specifically in interface customization. This topic falls under the category of Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC). The paper also discusses the development of models to learn individual preferences online, which involves machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of utility functions and elicitation techniques also suggests relevance to Information Retrieval (cs.IR) and Learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper discusses the sequential utility of intelligent assistance, which could relate to cybersecurity (cs.CY) in terms of decision-making and risk assessment.
